*** GIT AND GITHUB NOTES ***
A

## 1. Initial Setup

git config --global user.name "name"              => sets the name attached to your commits
git config --global user.email "email@gmail.com"  => sets the email attached to your commits
git config --global core.editor "code --wait"     => tells Git to use VS Code for commit messages etc.
git config --global core.autocrlf "input"         => normalizes line endings (Mac/Linux setting)
git config --global -e                            => opens the actual config file in VS Code to view/edit directly



## 2. The Git Stages (how Git sees your files)

Untracked (U) => Git sees the file exists, but isn't watching/saving it yet.
Staged/Added (A) => You've told Git "include this in my next snapshot."
Committed (C) => The file's current state is permanently saved in Git's history.

Think of it like a checkout process:
Untracked -> add to cart (stage) -> checkout (commit) -> saved forever in history



## 3. Checking Status & History

git status -s
=> Shows a short/compact view of what's changed — which files are staged,
   unstaged, or untracked. Good for a quick glance.

git log --oneline
=> Shows your commit history in a compact, one-line-per-commit format —
   easier to scan than the full git log.

git diff
=> Shows the EXACT line-by-line changes in your files BEFORE you stage/commit them.
   Use this to review what you're about to add — catches mistakes early.



## 4. Starting a New Project

Step 1: git init
=> Turns the current folder into a Git-tracked project. Creates a hidden
   .git folder that stores all history. Nothing is saved yet — Git is just
   "watching" now.

Step 2: Make a checkpoint (save point):
  a) git add filename       => stage the file (or "git add ." for all files)
  b) git commit -m "message" => permanently save the staged changes as a snapshot,
                                  with a description of what changed

git restore --staged filename   => undo "git add" but KEEP your changes (unlike reset --hard, which deletes them)

git commit --amend -m "new message"   => fix your LAST commit's message, or add a forgotten file to it, instead of making a whole new commit



## 5. Viewing & Reverting History

git log --oneline                => see all saved points/checkpoints
git log --oneline --graph        => see branch change graph
git reset --hard HEAD~1          => revert back to the previous checkpoint (discards changes)


## 6. Branches

git branch
=> Lists all branches in your project. The one with * next to it is your
   current branch — that's where any add/commit you do right now will land.

git branch branch-name
=> Create a branch (without switching to it)

git checkout -b branch-name
=> Create + switch to it in one step (this is what people actually use most)

git switch branch-name
=> Moves you to a different branch. Your files update to match whatever
   was last committed on that branch.

git restore filename
=> (modern replacement for "git checkout filename") Discards changes to ONE
   specific file, reverting it back to how it looked in the last commit.
   NOTE: git switch is ONLY for branches, never files.


* Adding files to a branch (just normal add + commit)

1. Switch to the branch first:
   git checkout branch-name   (or git switch branch-name)

2. Then work as usual:
   git add filename
   git commit -m "message"

=> Whatever branch you're currently on is where add/commit saves to.
   No special command needed — just switch first, then add/commit normally.
   A branch name has NOTHING to do with file names — files keep their
   normal names no matter which branch you're on.

git merge branch-name
=> Combines another branch's changes into the branch you're currently on.
   You merge a BRANCH, not a file/filename.
   Typically done after switching to "main": git switch main -> git merge feature-branch



## 7. Stashing (temporary draft of changes)

git stash
=> Temporarily saves your uncommitted changes aside (like a draft), and gives
   you a clean working folder — useful when you need to switch branches but
   aren't ready to commit yet.

git stash apply
=> Brings your stashed draft back into your current branch, so you can
   continue where you left off.

git stash clear
=> Deletes all stashed drafts permanently.



## 8. Ignoring Files

.gitignore (a file you create in your project)
=> Lists files/folders Git should NEVER track — like secrets, dependency
   folders, or system files. Prevents accidentally committing junk or
   sensitive data.

Example .gitignore contents:
.env
node_modules/
.DS_Store



## 9. Collaboration (this is where GitHub actually enters the picture)

NOTE: Everything in sections 1-8 above is LOCAL only — it happens entirely on
your own computer, in your own branch, whether or not GitHub is involved at all.
This section is the first time your work actually gets shared with GitHub / other people.

--- Person A — starts the project ---
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git remote add origin <repo-url>     => links your local folder to a GitHub repo
git push -u origin main               => uploads local main branch to GitHub

--- Person B — joins the project ---
git clone <repo-url>                  => downloads the whole project to their computer
git switch -c feature-login            => creates + switches to their OWN branch
[edit files]
git add .
git commit -m "Added login page"
git push -u origin feature-login       => uploads THEIR branch (not main) to GitHub
   NOTE: you push a BRANCH NAME, not a filename.

--- Person C (or A) — merges the work in ---
git fetch origin        => checks for new branches/changes on GitHub (does NOT merge)
git switch main           => go to main locally
git pull origin main       => make sure local main is fully up to date
git merge feature-login     => bring Person B's branch into main
git push origin main         => upload the updated main back to GitHub

--- Everyone else ---
git pull origin main    => get the newly merged changes onto their own computer

Key idea: nobody edits "main" directly. Everyone works on their OWN branch,
pushes that branch, and someone reviews + merges it into main. On GitHub itself,
this reviewing/merging step is usually done through a "Pull Request" instead of
typing merge commands manually — same underlying process, just with a review
step built in before the merge happens.


## 10. Real troubleshooting notes (from actually doing it)

Problem: git push / git pull said "Already up to date" even though I had
edited a file and expected it to upload.

Cause: I had NOT actually committed the file locally yet. The file existed
on disk but wasn't staged/committed — so Git had no new local commit to send.
Push only sends commits that exist locally and don't exist on GitHub yet.

Fix: had to do the full sequence before push actually had something to do:
   git add .
   git commit -m "message"
   git push origin main

Lesson: add + commit only save locally, on YOUR computer. GitHub has no idea
anything changed until you push. You can commit 100 times locally and GitHub
will still show the old version until push happens. Every update, every time,
needs all three steps — add, commit, push — no shortcuts.

--- .DS_Store cleanup (Mac-specific junk file) ---
echo ".DS_Store" > .gitignore
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Add gitignore for DS_Store"
git push origin main
=> stops Git from ever tracking macOS's auto-generated .DS_Store file again


--- Uploading files directly on github.com (drag-and-drop / "Add file") ---
This ALSO creates a real commit, same as git commit locally — GitHub just
does it for you through the website instead of the terminal. A repo built
this way works exactly the same as one built locally.

To continue working on it using terminal commands going forward:
   git clone <repo-url>    => downloads it to your computer
   [then use the normal add / commit / push flow from here on]

Git doesn't care HOW a commit was made (terminal vs website upload) —
only that it exists. Both are fully compatible with each other.


## 11. The IDEAL flow — uploading a brand new project to GitHub, start to finish

This is the clean sequence to follow from scratch, avoiding the
"already up to date" / unrelated histories confusion entirely.

Step 1: Create the repo on GitHub FIRST
   - Go to github.com -> New repository
   - Give it a name
   - IMPORTANT: do NOT check "Add a README" if you already have local files
     ready to push (this avoids the unrelated-histories problem entirely)
   - Click Create repository -> copy the repo URL it gives you

Step 2: Set up Git locally (in your project folder)
   git init
   git add .
   git commit -m "Initial commit"

Step 3: Connect local folder to the GitHub repo
   git remote add origin <repo-url>
   git branch -M main
      => renames local branch to "main" if it wasn't already

Step 4: Push it up
   git push -u origin main
      => the -u saves this connection, so next time you can just type "git push"

Step 5: Confirm
   - Refresh the repo page on github.com
   - Your files should now be visible there

--- From now on, every time you make changes ---
   git add .
   git commit -m "describe what changed"
   git push

--- If you DID start with a README already on GitHub (unrelated histories) ---
   git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
   git push -u origin main
   => merges GitHub's history with your local history, then this only
      needs to be done once, right at the start

Lesson: cleanest path is create the repo empty (no README) -> init locally
-> add/commit -> remote add -> push. Skips all the merge-conflict-with-README
confusion entirely.


## 12. Why things go wrong (real lesson learned)

Situation: followed steps correctly but git commit kept saying
"no changes added to commit" / git push kept saying "Everything up-to-date"
even though files were clearly changed.

Root causes found:
1. The folder already had an existing .git repo from before (git init said
   "Reinitialized existing Git repository" instead of creating a fresh one).
   Old leftover tracked/staged files were still sitting there.

2. Files got deleted/renamed OUTSIDE of git (via Finder/VS Code/terminal
   directly) instead of using git commands. Git doesn't watch the filesystem
   live — it only finds out when you run git status or git add.

3. THE BIG ONE: git commit does NOT auto-detect changes. It only commits
   whatever has already been staged with git add. If nothing is staged,
   commit does nothing — even if files were obviously edited/deleted/added.
   This is why several commits appeared to "do nothing."

GOLDEN RULE: git commit never guesses. It only saves exactly what git add
staged. No staging = commit is a no-op, and push will say "Everything
up-to-date" because there was nothing new to send in the first place.
